                  <note>
                     
                     <ab type="history">Zabīd is the name of  a town and an administrative district in the <placeName ref="LOC5977Tihama"/>
                        coastal plain of <placeName ref="LOC6387Yemen"/>. It is located 25 km from the<placeName ref="LOC5339RedSea"/> shore in area of fertile 
                        agricultural lands irrigated by<placeName ref="LOC6129WadiRi"/> in the north, <placeName ref="LOC6131WadiZa"/> to which it owes its name, in the south.
                        Zabīd was founded in the 9th century under the <persName ref="PRS11715Ziyadi"/>dynasty, from <date>819</date> to <date>1021</date> who made its political centre.
                        As early as the 10th-11th century Zabīd was recognized as one of the leading urban centres in the Islamic world.  Zabīd was taken by the <placeName ref="Q12560"/> 
                        who made it their chief <placeName ref="Q1163682"/>centre between <date>1538</date> and <date>1636</date>. During that period dynamic commercial,
                        political and religious interactions between <placeName ref="LOC6387Yemen"/> and North east Africa persisted. The Influence of Zabīd's religious academics on Islamic institutions 
                        and scholars in the Horn of Africa since 18th century can not be overstated. 
                           
                     </ab>
